<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> An Interview With: Scott Lingrell: Part 1.<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.95)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=19873'>SWCCG "Writing" Team</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=19873&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 3, 2006</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Article: An Interview with Scott Lingrell: Part 1<br />
Interviewee: Scott Lingrell<br />
Interviewer: Benjamin D. Kline<br />
<br />
<br />
Benjamin D. Kline: How&#39;d you get into the game (SW:CCG)?<br />
<br />
Scott Lingrell: I played magic with some friends (including John Lolli) and one day John and his old roommate bought some Premiere Starter Decks.  I liked the look of them and would look over the rule book Lak Sivrak (or however it was spelled) was a cool looking character.<br />
 <br />
<br />
BDK: When did you start playing?<br />
<br />
SL:John and I never really picked it up until Dagobah.  That was the first box of cards we bought. <br />
 <br />
Funny story, we opened all the packs and drafted the rares (1st pick got 1/4 - 2nd pick got 2/3).  I took IG_88 with the first pick (as he would have too because we thought he was broken...)  He took Yoda and Executor with picks 2 and 3.  Oh well :)<br />
<br />
 <br />
BDK: Early game thoughts? [Think Premier through Reflections]<br />
<br />
SL: I enjoyed the game immensely.  I never really started to do well until my first trip to Origins in 1997 playing a JP ETE deck.  Lost the final game (needed to win to make the final 2) but ended up in 8th place.  It started a string of events where I normally place well in larger events, while scrubbing out in the locals.  With John&#39;s help, we were able to really develop some good decks and we both got a chance to qualify for worlds a few times here and there.<br />
 <br />
<br />
BDK: Later game thoughts? [Reflections to Theed]<br />
<br />
SL: The game was still exciting, but there were obvious power issues.  I remember Steve Brentson playing a senate deck and just destroying everyone in pickup games with it.  The drains, the destiny power, everything was just over the top.<br />
 <br />
<br />
BDK: Thoughts on Decipher losing the license?<br />
<br />
SL: I think I would be happy if a company was able to get the production license if I could be involved somehow.  When decipher lost the license, the game was really kicking butt.  That year was RamapoCon 3 in June with a huge turnout and a lot of excitement at the other cons.  It worked out though with the game starting to thrive again (over the last year or so). <br />
 <br />
 <br />
BDK: RamapoCon? Give us the dirt!<br />
<br />
SL: One day, Ted P, had the battle of Midway, which had players from NJ, Albany and Philly (among others).  Ted knew some of the guys in Albany and our area and we thought it would be a great opportunity to have a big competition for bragging rights and some glass.  The event was very successful because it brought the best players from the region together. Afterwards, it continued with numerous events run by Ted P and other like Rich Haman, Marty Twigg and more.<br />
 <br />
One day, I decided to have an event like that at my college that would draw a large number of people with excellent prizes. It was run at my college, Ramapo College of NJ, and therefore I named it RamapoCon 99.   The first event had 45~ players from different areas and really was a hell of a time.<br />
 <br />
Next, I had Rcon II.  It was bigger and better.  I had players from a lot of different states including Juz, Bojo and Reitzel driving up from Decipher (Bojo was just a player then.).  I was able to get them put up in a hotel a few minutes away and fun was had by all.  With tons of prizes, glass, cards and more, it turned out to be a really good event with 66 players for the main event.  The amazing part is that Jon Chu won the first two RamapoCon main events.  It was just as impressive as worlds at any year giving the amount of top players there.<br />
 <br />
Just to give props to Coruscant.  At any one point we had so many amazing players like TJ Holman, Ray Bordier, Jon Chu, Chris and Brian Terwilliger, Matt and Dan Sokol, John Lolli, Greg Hodur, Chris Praskac, Marco Habert, Chris Janiak, Mike Dalton, Joe Young, the list goes on and on...<br />
 <br />
We definately beat out Yavin IV for the best region evah! :)  They were definately a top region at that time though.  For obvious reasons with Clint Hays, Steven Lewis, Jim Sells, Brian Rippetoe and more.  I think at one worlds event, Yavin and Coruscant had maybe 15 of 20 top placers for the Day 1 event.    It was insane.<br />
 <br />
RamapoCon 3 of course was the big daddy.  Plane trip to DCon (of course they canceled worlds though.) $1,000 DPC event, qualifier events for all 4 Decipher games.  It had about 200 different people for the different events.  It was by far the most amazing event.  If you read TReports from Gemme, Hayes and more, they all have given RCon 3 (with its plush dorm rooms) a top 2 best con ever rating.  RCon and FreedomCon are always 1 and 2 to anyone that went to these events.  Of course I was never able to do this by myself.  I had some of the best volunteers ever.   We also had some of the top players in the world show up, Bastian, Hawkins, Lewis, Chu, Twiggs, Bordier, Holman, Jankowski and more.  It was amazing.<br />
 <br />
People like Blythe and Tom H-K. Ted P, Rich Haman, Bart Robinson, Kim Caton and more.  Everyone worked tirelessly for those events to make them so fondly remembered by players that attended them.<br />
 <br />
<br />
BDK: Thoughts on the first couple of Virtual Sets?<br />
<br />
SL: I must be honest, I don’t think I was playing much in the beginning because of time commitments of getting married, starting a new job and life in general was quite busy.  I was very excited to see the new cards come out like random.rares being useful again (prophetess was a big one).<br />
<br />
 <br />
BDK: SecureRoute[v].... Tell us, how&#39;d you come up with it, what was the process like, in other words.... GIVE US THE DIRT!<br />
 <br />
SL: Decipher playtesting.  8 of us were flown into decipher 2 times. Chu, Hays, Lewis, Girard, Olson, Faust and some others I can’t remember.  One weekend I had to test WHAP in about 30+ games.  I lost every single game.  Every one.  It was the worst objective ever.  So I decided when I won the card design to really give the LS some options with the deck without making it obnoxious.  It really gives it power, but obviously can still get housed by EPP Maul and friends. <br />
 <br />
Neal Razi really played the deck to a T when Lush, him and I had a little tech group in place.  His modifications really made it better, but some tech like R2 & Threepio to make sure they never draw destiny = win.  Recyclicing Rebublicans was Neal’s deck if you want to Sagan it.<br />
 <br />
<br />
BDK: How did you get to be involved with the PC?<br />
<br />
SL: I was involved in PTing since post D*II and really wanted to contribute more.  Eventually I stepped in unofficially and helped the PC for a bit until Eric left and I came over officially ever since. <br />
 <br />
<br />
BDK: Active duties in the PC?<br />
<br />
SL: Well, I have overextended myself at times but with a great group of volunteers that help organize certain things, it really helps bring the game to the next level.  People like Simon and Henry (proofing), Sonn (Proofing, quizzes and more) You, J Taylor and Brandon (writing), Christoph and Matt (online play), Evan (website) and more.  Its really been a big leap in the game.<br />
 <br />
<br />
BDK: Designing Cards.... c&#39;mon, again, you know what we want.... (the dirt!)<br />
<br />
SL: Well, we have definitely gone through a bit transition on the design team.  When the new design document comes out, I will put it in an article or two for you guys. Its going to be interesting to see how the new version has changed a lot of how things are done, just like the version after that will be more detailed also.<br />
 <br />
<br />
BDK: Thoughts on the future of SW:CCG?<br />
 <br />
SL: Its very bright.  Online tournaments should be tested soon.  A new website, online rules database, Jasonmaas.net is getting an overhaul soon and more.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
----------<br />
Post Interview news from the Writing Team:<br />
<br />
As with much of the Players Committee, like the Virtual Set &quot;Redux&quot; soon to be released (target date of July), the Writing Team as well is going through some changes.<br />
<br />
We have been very sorry for the delay in articles, interviews, decks, and other such things.<br />
<br />
We are looking forward to providing you with high quality content in the upcoming months.<br />
<br />
<br />
You can look forward to Part 2 of this interview to be posted in a month or so. Both Scott Lingrell, and Benjamin D. Kline (editor for the Writing Team) have very busy schedules and hope you understand this.<br />
<br />
As always, if you want to help out in any way, you can contact the Writing Team here by d-mailing them. They are not actively looking for new members, although if you care to submit something to them, and they deem you are &#39;talented enough&#39; you could be given consideration and be added as a new member (provided you have the time, energy, and drive to do so.) Please, only serious d-mails.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
With the addition of Virtual Set: Redux to the game, you can then look forward to these forthcoming articles:<br />
<br />
* The Basics: Starting Interrupts<br />
